<TEXT>
a british frigate collided with a canadian support 
ship sunday during nato maneuvers off norway the ministry of 
defense said 
a ministry spokesman said there were no injuries in the 
collision between the hms penelope and the canadian vessel 
preserver he said the preserver was not damaged and would continue 
to take part in the exercise 
the penelope headed for rosyth on the scottish east coast where 
the extent of the damage would be determined 
the spokesman speaking on condition of anonymity said the 
collision took place during a refueling operation about 7 am 1 
am edt sunday in vestfjorden the waterway between the lofoten 
islands and the northwest norwegian coast 
penelope is a 3200ton leander class warship with 230 officers 
and crew the much larger preserver 24700 tons has a complement 
of 290 and is mainly used for refueling other ships at sea 
the vessels were taking part in teamwork 88 a nato exercise 
involving 45000 land sea and air personnel of the armed forces of 
nine nato countries 340 aircraft and 200 ships the exercise is 
designed to test naval warfare air force collaboration 
antisubmarine carrier and convoy operations and amphibious 
landings 
the exercise began aug 31 and runs through sept 21 
sundays collision was the second reported in nine days to a 
british warship 
the destroyer hms southampton was rammed and badly damaged sept 
3 in the gulf of oman by the british container ship tor bay it was 
protecting 
eleven sailors on the destroyer were injured three having 
broken bones but no one was hurt on the much larger merchantman 
</TEXT>
