<TEXT>
burundi president pierre buyoya has 
visited the area in northern burundi where at least 5000 people 
were killed last month in tribal violence radio burundi reported 
sunday 
the staterun radio said buyoya during his weekend tour 
commended doctors for helping the wounded in the districts of ntega 
and marangara the sites of the massacre of thousands of people of 
the majority hutu tribe in the warfare that began aug 14 
an estimated 55000 people fled into neighboring rwanda to 
escape the violence that claimed 5000 lives according to 
government estimates other sources have said the death toll was 
much higher 
radio burundi in a brief item monitored in nairobi said buyoya 
claimed the killings were caused by dissident hutus who infiltrated 
into the north to provoke attacks against the minority tutsi tribe 
buyoyas government had made the same allegation earlier 
the tutsis comprise only 15 percent of burundis population of 5 
million but control the tiny central african nations government 
and army about 84 percent of the population are hutus 
some burundi refugees in rwanda have said hutus initiated the 
killings by attacking tutsis in ntega but soldiers were responsible 
for most of the massacres that spread into marangara they said the 
troops began killing hutus in reprisal for the slain tutsis 
burundis government has acknowledged its military forces became 
involved but claims soldiers killed fewer than a dozen people and 
restored peace in the area by aug 17 
the two tribes are longtime enemies following a hutuled coup 
attempt in the former belgium colony in 1972 the tutsi massacred an 
estimated 100000 hutus 
</TEXT>
