<TEXT>
the struggle for civil rights remains 
alive although it has changed says one of several activists 
honored for their work in the 1960s 
the nature and the character of the movement has changed but 
these changes are merely part of a natural process and do not spell 
doom for our hopes said rep john lewis dga former chairman 
of the student nonviolent coordinating committee 
lewis who received an honorary doctorate at a convocation 
saturday opening williams colleges 196th academic year said the 
american people must elect leaders with the moral capacity of 
the rev martin luther king jr if civil rights are to improve with 
time 
we have lost some of our finest leaders but we are still very 
involved in that same movement for liberation said lewis who 
was jailed 40 times and severely beaten during the sixties for 
leading peaceful marches and demonstrations throughout the south 
our struggle is not for one day or one week or one year but 
for a lifetime if thats what it takes 
among thos honored saturday was rosa l parks whose refusal to 
surrender her seat to a white passenger on a montgomery ala bus 
sparked a boycott that was a milestone in the civil rights 
movement she received a standing ovation from the audience of 
1000 students faculty members and administrators 
also honored were the rev ralph d abernathy former president 
of the southern christian leadership conference and journalist 
charlayne huntergault the first black woman at the university of 
georgia 
