<TEXT>
a record 916 people tackled mount 
mckinley during the mountaineering season says the national park 
service which is thinking about putting another outhouse on north 
americas tallest mountain 
sanitation on the 20320foot mountain has been a growing 
concern said ranger roger robinson 
according to robinson 562 of the 916 people who registered to 
climb mckinley this spring and summer reported reaching the summit 
last year 817 climbers tested themselves against the mountain 
only about a third finished the climb 
two people died climbing mckinley this year robinson said 
don henry a 71yearold connecticut lawyer this year became 
the oldest person known to have made the top 
robinson attributed some of the increased mountaineering to 
foreigners who decided attractive currency exchange rates made this 
the year for the climb they had long wanted to make 
climbers began arriving in april and some waited until late 
july but most planned their trips for may and june 
were trying to get more people to come in july robinson 
said rangers attempting to deal with the environmental effects of 
increased activity want use of the mountain to be spread out 
the park service asks climbers to use plastic bags for human 
waste and put the bags in crevasses but officials dont know how 
many comply robinson said there are two latrines on mckinley one 
twothirds of the way up the peak the park service hopes to 
install an outhouse at 17000 feet next year 
