<TEXT>
two of the largest us computer manufacturers 
have won the first round in a fight with the air force to be 
reimbursed at taxpayers expense for their legal costs in 
challenging pentagon contracting procedures 
the general services administrations board of contract appeals 
in an aug 17 opinion obtained late last week decided that digital 
equipment corp and wang laboratories inc were entitled to some of 
the more than 1 million they are seeking but did not say how much 
rather in a partial victory for the air force the board 
ordered the firms to segregate legal expenses incurred in 
pursuing the portion of the original challenge that they won and 
said they could recover only those costs 
if the two sides cant reach a settlement the board said 
additional proceedings will be held to fix the award 
the air force had asked the board to reject completely digitals 
claim for 830330 and wangs demand for 210000 
the sixpage opinion written by administrative judge vincent a 
labella and endorsed by two other judges marks the latest chapter 
in a twoyearold battle over what has been called the computer 
contract of the century 
the air force intends to buy about 20000 minicomputers for use 
by all the armed services at cost of up to 45 billion the 
contract is expected to be awarded in the next month or so 
digital and wang like most other industry firms expressed an 
interest in bidding on the contract in early 1987 but before the 
bidding deadline passed they filed a challenge with the gsa board 
charging that the air force had rigged the competition 
the companies complained specifically about a requirement the 
computers operate on a unix or unixcompatible program unix is a 
proprietary system developed by american telephone amp telegraph co 
and widely licensed to other vendors 
the air force says unix compatibility is essential if the 
military is ever to standardize its computer systems 
the gsa board in its initial ruling last october backed the 
air force for the most part concluding that unix had become an 
industry standard the decision here is not unlike a 
determination to specify either vhs or beta video recorders it 
said 
but the board also said the air force should have spelled out in 
greater detail how it intended to use an atampt test program to 
determine contract compliance 
the air force did that in november when it issued two pages of 
amendments to its solicitation before restarting the competition 
digital and wang citing their partial victory then filed requests 
for reimbursement of all legal expenses stemming from the challenge 
digital said failure to reimburse would discourage future 
challenges and result in loss of effective enforcement of the 
procurement laws 
the loser would be competition and thus ultimately the 
taxpayer the company said 
air force lawyers countered that digital and wang had lost 
this case after prevailing on a single insignificant issue as 
evidence they pointed to the two companiess withdrawal from the 
competition in january 
the board disagreed saying that only after the air force 
corrected its solicitation were digital and wang able to determine 
whether they should compete on the governments terms 
their challenge produced the benefit of full and open 
competition which is the touchstone and objective of procurement 
law it said 
air force attorney kevin vincent said the boards decision was 
wrong but that the air force had not decided what to do next 
wang spokesman joseph roy indicated that the air force and the 
companies had begun discussing a possible settlement as urged by 
the gsa board 
a spokesman for digital failed to return a phone call friday 
</TEXT>
