<TEXT>
consider yourself warned 
a hefty helping of granola or wholewheat bread could contain 
enough natural lsd to produce mild high the dragons of fairy tales 
really may have existed and a violent collision between earth and 
a swarm of comets is overdue 
welcome to the weird and wonderful world of the british 
association for the advancement of science which concluded its 
annual meeting at oxford university 50 miles northwest of london 
the association was established in 1831 to promote general 
interest in all branches of science 
while it still produces some of the most important and advanced 
research in britain its annual meetings are also a forum for more 
farfetched concepts designed to stimulate debate 
for example eating eight to 10 slices of wholewheat bread or a 
large bowl of granola or bran flakes in one sitting may induce a 
mild euphoria because of wheats natural lsd content said dr 
david conning director of the british nutrition foundation 
lsd a popular hallucinogen in the 1960s is produced naturally 
by ergot a common fungal infestation of wheat that may survive 
food processing conning told the meeting 
he said a highbran diet could result in a daily consumption of 
100 micrograms of lsd or four times the minimum dose needed to 
produce an effect on an inexperienced user of the drug 
david unwin of the palaeontological institute in moscow told the 
conference the dragons of fairy tales may have existed he said 
they were flying dinosaurs with 16foot wingspans and dominated the 
skies 140 million years ago 
speaking of dinosaurs walter alvarez a professor at the 
university of california at berkeley said the only possible 
explanation for their extinction 65 million years ago was a 
sixmile wide asteroid hitting earth with an explosive force equal 
to 100 million megatons of tnt 
as proof alvarez cites the amount of the metallic chemical 
iridium in rocks laid down at that time iridium is rare in the 
earths crust he said and the high levels found in rocks of that 
era must have come from an extraterrestrial source 
dr victor clube an astrophysicist at oxford university warned 
that a collision between earth and a swarm of comets is overdue and 
will certainly happen within 100 years in a worstcase scenario 
it will produce effects similar to a nuclear war he warned 
meanwhile mans best friend got a new look at the meeting 
dr willem hackmann of oxfords museum of the history of science 
exhibited a computerized watchdog that uses ultrasound or 
highfrequency sound waves to detect intruders 
hackmann said the watchdogs snarl gets louder and louder as the 
intruder approaches but he admitted the sound is more like a 
rumbling thunderstorm than a canine bark there are hopes of 
improving that he said 
