<TEXT>
auto analysts say general motors corp is using 
fewer outside parts suppliers while keeping more of its 40 billion 
annual parts production within the company 
improved unionmanagement relations and the strong hand of gm 
president robert stempel are behind the shift away from 
outsourcing long a target of united auto workers union 
criticism 
in every single plant labor and management are sitting down 
together and reviewing problems and putting programs in place 
said donald ephlin a uaw vice president and head of the unions gm 
department that never happened before 
gm continues making more of its own parts than do ford motor co 
or chrysler corp the no1 automaker was producing 72 percent of 
its own parts as recently as may compared with 54 percent at ford 
and 39 percent at chrysler according to the university of 
michigans office for the study of automotive transportation 
a year earlier gm was planning to reduce internal parts 
production to 50 percent by 1992 said david cole director of the 
university office gms apparent reversal has drawn new criticism 
from some of the outside parts makers it once relied upon 
smaller suppliers will go out of business and larger ones will 
shift their work toward ford and chrysler said the chief executive 
of one major supplier who asked that his name not be used 
a spokesman for gms components division which employs 200000 
workers denied the automaker deliberately had brought more parts 
production back within the gm fold 
the components group is fighting for every piece of business 
it can get jerry bishop said were fighting for it within gm 
and outside gm 
stempel however made his position on the issue clear last year 
during his first news conference as president saying my 
objective is to get competitive not to outsource and close 
under stempel gm has looked beyond the immediate bottom line of 
the cost of parts said maryanne keller a new yorkbased industry 
analyst 
gm officials earlier accepted this simplistic rationalization 
that went were paying 28 an hour for labor and outside 
companies are paying 8 an hour so no wonder were not cost 
competitive she said 
now they have a broader view of the cost equation that a lot 
of the problems result from bad organization and bad management 
philosophy keller said that means they have it within their 
own power to cure the problems and in many cases without spending 
a lot of money 
top gm officials were unavailable for comment but a uaw member 
who spoke on condition of anonymity said chairman roger smith 
expressed his support for gms new approach at a meeting two weeks 
ago with union officials 
a lot of what smith talked about was family about the fact 
that workers are family and suppliers are not and that from now 
on family is going to be taken care of first the uaw member 
said 
